The cancellation rates based on market segment of the customer and the distribution channel the booking was made are quite interesting. For the market segment, the cancellation rates seem fairly consistent with the exception of Group bookings which have a cancellation rate nearly double the nearest segment (Online TA).Interestingly, when broken down into customer type, Group bookings have a much lower cancellation rate than the group market segment, a possible error is apparent in how the markets are categorized between these two measures (market segment vs customer type descriptions do not provide explanation in Kaggle). We see a similar scenario for the distribution sample, where corporate, direct, and GDS are all similar, but TA/TO (travel agents/tour operators) channel is nearly double that of any other channel excluding the undefined customers.

#Graphs cancellation rates by deposit type

The cancellation rates for each deposit type is incredible interesting. Among those with non-refundable deposits almost all of those customers ended up canceling their room, about 0.994. This made us doubt that the data was labeled incorrectly, but found in a Kaggle discussion post that the author of the paper, which the dataset is from, addressed this issue: “…through analysis of the “Nonrefundable” (DepositType) canceled bookings in some Asiatic countries (Country) and from certain distribution channels (DistributionChannel and Agent), it is possible to understand why so many “Nonrefundable” bookings are canceled. These bookings are usually made through OTA using false or invalid credit card details. These bookings are issued as support for requests for visas to enter the country (a hotel booking is mandatory for applying for a Portuguese entry visa)." This is important information to consider when forecasting demand to make demand-management decisions.

#Histogram of total number of guests for each hotel

Above are histograms for the number of adults, children, babies, and all guests total for each hotel. Overwhelmingly the most common amount of adults is two, likely indicating that people typically travel as a couple or partnership. Since such a large portion of people travel without children or babies, the children and babies histogram start at 1. Most bookings with children only have 1, while the proportion of people have two children is much closer to one child for the resort hotel, possibly due to more people traveling to the resort for non-business purposes. For babies, it is overwhelmingly dominated by having only one baby for a booking. Besides the number of children distinction already mentioned, the distributions for each hotel are quite similar.

5 Insights

  • Customers who were planning to stay in the city hotels tended to cancel bookings more than those planning to stay in the resort hotels.

  • Majority of customers who canceled their bookings chose non-refundable options.

  • Both types of hotels would need to have more Type A rooms, which is the most sought-after room type among all customers.

  • Customers with children tend to have breakfast options more than customers who do not.

  • Customers booked through agents pay more on average, but the cancellation rate is also high. Customers booked through agents pay more on average, but the cancellation rate is also high.

5.1 # Business Implication

  • Hotels have insight into customers’ meal preferences and room preferences, which will help hotels consider package options and conduct events to attract customers to generate more revenue.

  • Hotels can conduct additional research, such as a TA/TO survey, to gain insight into why customers who booked a room through agents have a higher cancellation rate. It will help them analyze the booking rates and potential income.
